<DOC><DOCNO> AP890914-0049 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 0311EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-14 0302</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0315</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Declines, Nikkei Up</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar declined against the yen Thursday, whilethe key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose moderately.   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average regained 114.94 points, or0.34 percent, closing at 34,401.80. The index had lost 45.94 pointsthe previous day.   The dollar ended trading at 145.85 yen, down 0.85 yen fromWednesday's close of 147.03 yen. The currency opened at 146.05 yenand moved between 145.50 yen and 146.43 yen.   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's lower opening to itsovernight decline, mainly against major European currencies, onoverseas markets.   ``The dollar started falling against the yen as foreign investorssold it against the West German mark,'' said a Bank of Tokyo trader,speaking on condition of anonymity.   The currency fell further as the Bank of Japan conducted adollar-selling intervention to halt the dollar's excessive rise whensome investors attempted to buy it back, he said.   The Bank of Japan reportedly sold some $300 million. The centralbank does not comment on its monetary actions.   Other traders said many market players were sitting on thesidelines as the market awaited a spate of major U.S. economicfigures this week.   Among major data to be released by the U.S. government were thenation's August retail sales, due out later Thursday in Washington,and the July merchandise trade figures, due Friday.   On the stock exchange, the market's key index rose as marketplayers were reassured by the yen's recovery against the dollar,said Kazuyuki Suzuki, a Daiwa Securities dealer.   ``The yen's rebound pushed down the short-term interest ratehere, which also reassured participants and encouraged them to buystocks,'' he said.   But trading was light ahead of a three-day weekend startingFriday, Respect for the Aged Day, a national holiday, Suzuki said.  </TEXT></DOC>